solution.p:
By applying Gauss's law you should convince yourself that the magnitude of electric field of a charges shell depends on the distance r from the center of the shell with direction being radial from the center of the sphere.
E(r) = \begin{cases} 0 \amp r \lt R\\ \dfrac{1}{4\pi\epsilon_0}\, \dfrac{Q}{r^2} \amp r\gt R. \end{cases}
For directions, we will assume Q to be positive for our calculations.
